Definition:
Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) is a core AWS (Amazon Web Services) service that provides resizable compute capacity in the cloud. In simple terms, it lets you run virtual servers â€” called EC2 instances â€” to host applications, websites, or workloads without managing physical hardware.

ğŸš€ Key Features

Scalability:
Quickly increase or decrease the number or size of instances based on demand.

Pay-as-you-go:
You pay only for the compute time you use â€” no upfront costs.

Multiple Instance Types:
Choose from general-purpose, compute-optimised, memory-optimised, or GPU instances depending on your workload.

Elastic Load Balancing (ELB):
Distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances for high availability.

Auto Scaling:
Automatically adjusts the number of instances to handle traffic changes.

Security:
Integrated with AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM), Security Groups, and VPC for controlled access.

